    "title": "What This Document Did to Creditors",
    "url": "docs/doc1-covenant-strip.html#sec-impact",
    "summary": "This four-page document represents one of the most aggressive covenant-stripping transactions in the history of high-yield debt. Here is the total damage: Covenants Deleted (7 of 7): Limitation on Indebtedness -- AMC can now borrow unlimited amounts...",
    "keywords": "",
    "content": "This four-page document represents one of the most aggressive covenant-stripping transactions in the history of high-yield debt. Here is the total damage: Covenants Deleted (7 of 7): Limitation on Indebtedness -- AMC can now borrow unlimited amounts ahead of these notes Restricted Payments -- Cash can flow to equity holders at will Limitation on Liens -- All assets can be pledged to other creditors Affiliate Transactions -- Self-dealing is unrestricted Senior Subordinated Debt Limitation -- Unlimited dilution at this level Future Guarantors -- No new subsidiaries will ever guarantee these notes Change of Control -- No put right if the company is sold Events of Default Deleted (6 of ~10): Cross-default, judgment default, guarantee invalidity, subsidiary bankruptcy, and covenant breach triggers -- all gone Only payment default and company-level bankruptcy remain as triggers Guarantees Released: All subsidiary guarantees immediately terminated These notes went from a claim against the entire AMC enterprise to an unsecured, unguaranteed claim against the holding company Merger Covenant Gutted: AMC can merge into any entity with only self-certification, no financial health tests Strategic Purpose: This cleared the path for AMC's 2020 restructuring. The exchanging holders got new 10%/12% Second Lien Secured Notes with actual collateral. The holdouts were left with a covenant-free, guarantee-free unsecured instrument against a company in severe financial distress during COVID-19. This is the textbook \"exit consent\" playbook."
