    "summary": "Robertshaw is considered one of the most aggressive recent LMEs: Non-Pro-Rata Uptier Exchange: Available only to select lenders, providing new super-priority debt at a subsidiary level, enhanced collateral, and structural seniority through...",
    "keywords": "",
    "content": "Robertshaw is considered one of the most aggressive recent LMEs: Non-Pro-Rata Uptier Exchange: Available only to select lenders, providing new super-priority debt at a subsidiary level, enhanced collateral, and structural seniority through intercompany lending. Subsidiary Structure Manipulation: New intermediate holding company subsidiaries were created; assets and operations were reorganized to create structural priority for new debt. Value moved to entities where participating lenders had priority claims. Sponsor Co-Investment: One Rock invested additional capital alongside participating lenders as rhetorical justification. Exclusion of Non-Participating Lenders: Remaining lenders found themselves structurally disadvantaged with reduced collateral and effective subordination without consent. Key Provisions Exploited: - Subsidiary designation and asset transfer flexibility - Absence of blocker language for non-pro-rata exchanges - Majority amendment provisions for collateral/guarantee modifications - The distinction between “contractual subordination” (might require unanimous consent) and “structural subordination” (might not)"
