    "url": "research/case-studies.html#sec-key-2025-trends",
    "summary": "Cooperation agreements among lenders. Lenders now enter agreements at facility inception, pre-committing to collective action and restricting individual participation in non-pro-rata exchanges. LME as bankruptcy trigger. Courts increasingly...",
    "keywords": "",
    "content": "Cooperation agreements among lenders. Lenders now enter agreements at facility inception, pre-committing to collective action and restricting individual participation in non-pro-rata exchanges. LME as bankruptcy trigger. Courts increasingly recognize that LMEs can be the proximate cause of bankruptcy. Several 2024-2025 cases involved companies filing within months of completing an LME. “Trap door” provisions. Majority lenders strip minority protections through sequential seemingly innocuous amendments that cumulatively eviscerate protections. The “Pari Plus” structure. Evolution of the double-dip: pari passu on existing claims PLUS priority on new money PLUS intercompany claim – a triple claim. Cross-border LME complexity. Using foreign jurisdictions (e.g., English law schemes of arrangement) to effectuate LME-like transactions that might be challenged under U.S. law. Software/SaaS LME wave. Following Pluralsight, multiple Vista Equity and Thoma Bravo-backed software companies from the 2021 LBO vintage face LME activity."
