    "url": "research/countermeasures.html#sec-21-the-attack-uptier-priming-transactions",
    "summary": "In the Serta Simmons Bedding transaction (June 2020), a majority group of term loan lenders (>50%) agreed to amend the credit agreement to permit a new superpriority tranche of debt. Non-participating minority lenders were effectively subordinated...",
    "keywords": "",
    "content": "In the Serta Simmons Bedding transaction (June 2020), a majority group of term loan lenders (>50%) agreed to amend the credit agreement to permit a new superpriority tranche of debt. Non-participating minority lenders were effectively subordinated without their consent. The majority argued this was permissible under standard amendment provisions requiring only majority lender approval. How it works mechanically: 1. Borrower identifies willing majority lenders (typically >50% but <100%) 2. Majority lenders amend the credit agreement to (a) create a new “superpriority” lien basket, and (b) modify the intercreditor/waterfall provisions 3. Majority lenders roll existing loans into the new superpriority tranche, often with a small new money component 4. Non-participating lenders are subordinated – their first-lien loans are now effectively second-lien Key precedent: In Serta Simmons, the Southern District of New York initially dismissed the excluded lenders’ claims (2022), but this was later reversed on appeal. The case eventually resulted in a bankruptcy filing where the priming was contested. In Mitel Networks (2023), a similar uptier was executed. TripAdvisor/Liberty (2024) featured an open-market purchase twist."
