    "keywords": "",
    "content": "In the J.Crew transaction (2017), the company transferred its most valuable asset – the J.Crew trademark and intellectual property portfolio – to an unrestricted subsidiary that was outside the credit agreement’s restricted group. This IP was then used as collateral for new financing at the unrestricted subsidiary, effectively moving value beyond the reach of existing secured lenders. How the dropdown works: 1. Borrower designates (or creates) an unrestricted subsidiary 2. Borrower transfers valuable assets (IP, real estate, key contracts) to the unrestricted subsidiary via a “permitted investment” 3. The unrestricted subsidiary is not bound by the credit agreement’s covenants or lien restrictions 4. The unrestricted subsidiary issues new debt secured by the transferred assets 5. Existing lenders lose collateral value; new creditors at the unrestricted sub have priority over the transferred assets Subsequent examples: Travelport (2020), PetSmart/Chewy (2018-2020 – Chewy IP was at unrestricted sub level)"
