    "summary": "A “double-dip” occurs when a borrower creates structural layering through intercompany transactions that effectively give certain creditors two claims on the same pool of assets. How it works (classic formulation): 1. A restricted subsidiary (“Sub...",
    "keywords": "",
    "content": "A “double-dip” occurs when a borrower creates structural layering through intercompany transactions that effectively give certain creditors two claims on the same pool of assets. How it works (classic formulation): 1. A restricted subsidiary (“Sub A”) borrows from new creditors 2. Sub A makes an intercompany loan to its parent or an affiliate (“Sub B”) 3. The intercompany loan is secured by Sub B’s assets 4. New creditors now have (a) a direct claim against Sub A, and (b) an indirect claim against Sub B via the intercompany loan 5. In a bankruptcy, the new creditors effectively receive distributions from two entities on account of what is economically one claim Landmark examples: - Envision Healthcare (2023): KKR-backed Envision used intercompany loan structures to create priority for new money investors, which was later challenged in bankruptcy - Incora/Wesco Aircraft (2022): Complex intercompany structures used in connection with priming transaction - Robertshaw (2023): Double-dip structure contested in bankruptcy"
