    "content": "4.2.1 Restrictions on Intercompany Loans That Create Priority No Restricted Subsidiary shall make any Intercompany Loan to any other Restricted Subsidiary or to the Borrower if: (a) such Intercompany Loan is secured by Liens on the assets of the recipient that are pari passu with or senior to the Liens securing the Obligations; (b) such Intercompany Loan would have the effect of providing the creditors of the lending Restricted Subsidiary with a claim against the assets of the recipient that is pari passu with or senior to the claims of the Lenders under this Agreement; (c) the proceeds of such Intercompany Loan are used, directly or indirectly, to repay, prepay, redeem, or acquire any Indebtedness that is junior to the Obligations. 4.2.2 “No Double-Dip” Covenant Comprehensive formulation (2024+ best practice): SECTION [X]. No Double-Dip Financing. (a) The Borrower shall not, and shall not permit any Restricted Subsidiary to, directly or indirectly, incur, create, or permit to exist any Indebtedness, Lien, or other obligation or arrangement that would have the effect of providing any creditor or group of creditors with: (i) both a secured claim against one Loan Party and a secured or unsecured claim against another Loan Party arising from, or in connection with, the same economic transaction or series of related transactions (whether structured as an intercompany loan, guarantee, contribution, or otherwise); (ii) a claim against any Loan Party that is effectively senior to the Obligations by virtue of being supported by intercompany obligations that have priority over, or are structurally senior to, the Obligations; (iii) an effective lien priority that exceeds the priority such creditor would have had if it had simply lent directly to the relevant Loan Party. (b) For purposes of this Section, \"Double-Dip Financing\" includes, without limitation, any arrangement whereby: (i) a Restricted Subsidiary incurs Indebtedness and lends all or a portion of the proceeds thereof (directly or through one or more intermediaries) to the Borrower or another Restricted Subsidiary on a secured or guaranteed basis; (ii) the creditors of such Indebtedness would, in a bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding, have claims against more than one Loan Party arising from the same economic transaction; or (iii) the effect of such arrangement is to create structural or contractual priority for certain creditors over the Lenders with respect to the same Collateral. (c) Nothing in this Section shall prohibit ordinary course intercompany transactions solely among Loan Parties that do not involve external Indebtedness. 4.2.3 Intercompany Loan Subordination All Intercompany Loans from any Restricted Subsidiary to the Borrower or any other Restricted Subsidiary shall be (a) unsecured, (b) subordinated in right of payment to the Obligations, and (c) subject to a subordination agreement in form and substance reasonably satisfactory to the Administrative Agent, which shall provide that..."
