    "content": "Traditional credit agreements designated certain fundamental provisions as “sacred rights” that could not be amended without unanimous lender consent (or consent of each affected lender). These were narrowly drawn: Traditional Sacred Rights (requiring each lender’s or each affected lender’s consent): 1. Reduction of principal amount of loans 2. Extension of maturity date 3. Reduction of interest rate or fees 4. Extension of payment dates 5. Release of all or substantially all collateral 6. Release of all or substantially all guarantees Everything else – including lien priority, payment waterfall, pro-rata sharing, and subordination – could typically be modified by “Required Lenders” (usually defined as lenders holding >50% of outstanding obligations)."
