    "summary": "The Problem: “Yank-a-bank” provisions allow the borrower to replace lenders who refuse to consent to amendments requested by the Required Lenders. Pre-2020, there was ambiguity about whether yank-a-bank could be used to eliminate blocking positions...",
    "keywords": "",
    "content": "The Problem: “Yank-a-bank” provisions allow the borrower to replace lenders who refuse to consent to amendments requested by the Required Lenders. Pre-2020, there was ambiguity about whether yank-a-bank could be used to eliminate blocking positions for sacred right matters. The Fix (2023+ Standard): SECTION [X]. REPLACEMENT OF LENDERS. (a) The Borrower shall have the right to replace any Lender that (i) has refused to consent to an amendment, modification, supplement, or waiver that requires the consent of Required Lenders and has been approved by the Required Lenders (a \"Non-Consenting Lender\"), provided that: (1) such replacement shall not be permitted if the relevant amendment, modification, supplement, or waiver would constitute a modification to a Sacred Right provision (as set forth in Section [X](a)(i) through (xvi) above); (2) no replacement may be made if the effect of such replacement would be to reduce the aggregate principal amount of Loans held by Lenders who have not consented to such amendment below the threshold required to block such amendment; (3) the replacement lender shall assume all of the replaced lender's rights and obligations and shall pay to the replaced lender an amount equal to the outstanding principal, accrued interest, and fees owed to such replaced lender."
