    "summary": "Uptier transaction / Non-pro-rata uptier: A transaction in which a majority group of lenders exchanges existing debt for new super-priority debt, effectively subordinating the remaining (excluded) lenders Drop-down transaction: A transaction in...",
    "keywords": "",
    "content": "Uptier transaction / Non-pro-rata uptier: A transaction in which a majority group of lenders exchanges existing debt for new super-priority debt, effectively subordinating the remaining (excluded) lenders Drop-down transaction: A transaction in which the borrower transfers valuable assets to a new subsidiary (typically unrestricted), which then issues new debt to select creditors Double-dip: A structure allowing a creditor to assert claims at both parent and subsidiary level, effectively increasing recovery Open market purchase: A purchase of debt on the open market; exception to pro rata sharing extensively litigated and now largely defunct for LME purposes Sacred rights / Unanimous consent provisions: Provisions requiring each affected lender’s consent (e.g., maturity, principal, priority, AOSA collateral release) AOSA: “All or substantially all” – refers to collateral release thresholds requiring unanimous consent Pro rata sharing: Requirement that payments and distributions be made equally to all lenders in a class Serta blocker: A credit agreement provision explicitly prohibiting non-pro-rata uptier exchanges without affected lender consent J.Crew blocker: A provision limiting asset transfers to unrestricted subsidiaries Implied covenant of good faith and fair dealing: Implied contractual duty not to deprive the counterparty of the benefit of the bargain Equitable subordination (Section 510(c)): Bankruptcy court power to subordinate claims of creditors who engaged in inequitable conduct Section 225 proceeding: Delaware Chancery Court proceeding to resolve disputed board elections DIP financing (Section 364): Post-petition financing with super-priority status Intercreditor agreement (ICA): Agreement governing relative rights and priorities of different creditor classes Required lenders: The threshold (typically simple majority by outstanding principal) needed to amend most credit agreement provisions Unrestricted subsidiary (unsub): A subsidiary not governed by credit documents, treated as an outside entity This research brief is compiled from publicly available court filings, law firm analyses, market commentary, and the Octus article in your case competition materials. My training data extends through early-mid 2025. The Octus article dated August 25, 2025 provides the most current information in this compilation. Any developments after mid-2025 should be independently verified through current legal databases and counsel. This brief covers all eight areas you requested. A few notes on limitations and context for your case competition: WebSearch and WebFetch were unavailable , so I could not pull the very latest 2026 decisions. The analysis through mid-2025 is drawn from my training data and is supplemented by the Octus article ( /Users/diego/school/binghamton-non-school/BRx/Spring26CaseComp/txt_output/Case Competition Materials (AMC) 2/AMC and Del Monte LMEs_ Transactions and Bankruptcy Impact.txt ) in your case materials, which is dated..."
