    "content": "Sacred Rights: Require unanimous consent to amend – maturity extension, principal reduction, interest rate reduction, pro rata sharing changes, release of all/substantially all collateral or guarantees. Required Lender: Typically >50% of outstanding loans. Can approve amendments, direct agent action, accelerate debt. Permitted Investments / Restricted Payments: Credit agreement baskets that LMEs exploit to transfer assets to unrestricted subsidiaries, incur subsidiary-level debt, and make intercompany loans. Intercreditor Agreements: Govern priority of liens/payments between creditor classes, standstill periods, turnover provisions, and DIP consent rights. AMC’s intercreditor agreement between 1L and 2L was central to the excluded noteholder litigation. Open Market Purchase Exception: Allows debt repurchase without pro rata offering to all lenders. The Fifth Circuit’s Serta decision narrowed this exception, finding privately negotiated exchanges with select lenders do not qualify. This research is grounded in the actual AMC and Del Monte transaction mechanics documented in your case materials (particularly the Octus/Reorg analysis at /Users/diego/school/binghamton-non-school/BRx/Spring26CaseComp/Case Competition Materials (AMC) 2/AMC and Del Monte LMEs_ Transactions and Bankruptcy Impact.pdf ) and the BRx lecture materials on restructuring solutions ( /Users/diego/school/binghamton-non-school/BRx/Spring26CaseComp/Slideshows/Week6_Rx_Solutions.pdf ). The AMC-specific capital structure data is drawn from the Octus summary tables showing pre/post transaction metrics."
