    "keywords": "",
    "content": "Scenario A: Out-of-Court Refinancing Likelihood: Very Low - Would require willing lenders to refinance ~$3B+ at a leverage of 19.4x - No institutional market for cinema credits at these leverage levels - Anti-priming sacred rights block non-consensual priming transactions - Unrestricted Subsidiary prohibition (DOC 4, Sec 9.02(b)(xi)) blocks further drop-downs - Only viable if EBITDA doubles AND rates decline significantly Scenario B: Amend-and-Extend Likelihood: Low-Moderate - Extend TL maturity beyond October 2028 to provide more runway - BUT: Maturity Date is a sacred right (DOC 4, Sec 9.02(b)(iii)) — requires each affected Lender’s consent - Springing Maturity Condition is also a sacred right (Sec 9.02(b)(xvii)) — each Lender - Would need essentially 100% TL lender participation - Could be combined with interest reduction (also sacred right) - Sweetener: fees, small paydown, collateral enhancements Scenario C: Consensual Exchange Offer Likelihood: Moderate - Offer creditors new instruments with longer maturity, potentially lower face - Trade existing claims for: (a) new reduced-face notes + (b) equity + (c) cash sweep mechanism - DOC 2 holders (trading at 108.45) might accept par-for-par with extended maturity - DOC 7 holders (trading at 89.19) might accept discount exchange for priority improvement - Challenge: getting all four creditor groups to agree simultaneously Scenario D: Chapter 11 Prepackaged Bankruptcy Likelihood: Moderate-High - Pre-negotiate plan with majority creditors, file with plan in hand - Advantage: cram-down allows non-consenting minorities to be bound - Advantage: can address all four instruments simultaneously - Advantage: can reject unprofitable leases (operating lease liabilities: $4.1B PV) - Risk: business disruption, vendor/supplier panic, box office dependency - Key question: file AMC only, Muvico only, or both? Scenario E: Full Chapter 11 Restructuring Likelihood: Moderate (if prepack fails) - Free-fall filing with no pre-arranged plan - DIP financing needed (~$500-800M estimated) - Anti-priming sacred rights (DOC 4/7) require pro rata DIP participation offer — may complicate DIP process - Enterprise value fight: 8x vs. 10x vs. 12x EBITDA → swing of $640M in recovery - Substantive consolidation fight: Muvico creditors resist, TL holders may favor - Likely outcome: equitization of junior tranches, TL takes equity + reduced new debt Scenario F: Muvico Asset Sale / Theater Divestiture Likelihood: Low (as standalone) - Sell individual theater portfolios to Cinemark, Regal, or private equity - DOC 7 asset sale cap ($20M/$50M) severely limits this without creditor consent - IP sacred rights prevent separating theaters from the AMC brand - Most likely as part of Chapter 11 Section 363 sale - Potential acquirers: Cinemark (natural buyer), Apollo (private equity), Saudi PIF"
